WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:07.980
Oxford Bookworms, Stage 1. The Omega Files. Short Stories. by

00:07.980 --> 00:10.280
Jennifer Bassett. Read by

00:10.280 --> 00:16.660
Gareth Armstrong. Published and copyright, Oxford University Press, 2007.

00:31.580 --> 00:40.300
EDI, European Department of Intelligence. There were two of them,

00:41.320 --> 00:42.760
Hawker and Jude.

00:43.820 --> 00:51.100
They had no other names, just Hawker and Jude. They

00:51.100 --> 00:56.700
were young, fast and clever. They worked

00:56.700 --> 01:04.060
for EDI in the European government. You know about the

01:04.060 --> 01:08.440
Americans CIA and the Russians KGB?

01:09.580 --> 01:18.300
Well, this was EDI, the European Department of Intelligence. Big

01:18.300 --> 01:21.460
Secrets. Very strange secrets.

01:22.460 --> 01:28.460
The Secrets of the Omega Files. They don't get into

01:28.460 --> 01:33.160
the newspapers, and most people never hear about them.

01:34.280 --> 01:42.360
Most people don't know anything about EDI. In the early

01:42.360 --> 01:46.060
years, Hawker and Jude traveled a lot.

01:46.060 --> 01:57.060
Brussels, Strasbourg, Rome, Delhi, Washington, North Africa, South America, Australia,

01:57.740 --> 02:05.780
no home, no family, just work. They worked for the

02:05.780 --> 02:09.490
top man in the Brussels office of EDI,

02:10.350 --> 02:17.310
and only for him. He was called Arla. Nobody knew

02:17.310 --> 02:20.370
his real name, or much about him.

02:21.530 --> 02:26.910
Some said he was Latvian. Others said he was from

02:26.910 --> 02:33.310
another planet. He always gave the hard jobs to Hawker

02:33.310 --> 02:39.070
and Jude. The jobs with questions, but not many answers.

02:40.850 --> 02:42.150
The Omega Files.

02:44.170 --> 02:49.090
When I met them, many years later, Hawker and Jude

02:49.090 --> 02:54.190
were about 70 years old. They lived very quietly

02:54.190 --> 03:00.130
in a little white house on a Greek island. They

03:00.130 --> 03:05.730
went walking, swimming, fishing. They sat in the sun

03:05.730 --> 03:12.450
and slept a lot. At first, they didn't want to

03:12.450 --> 03:14.090
talk about their work.

03:15.090 --> 03:21.830
We can't, said Jude. Our work was secret. It's all

03:21.830 --> 03:26.010
in the government files, and nobody can read them.

03:27.190 --> 03:31.830
After 30 years, I said, people can read all secret

03:31.830 --> 03:32.990
government files.

03:33.950 --> 03:39.950
Not these files, Hawker said. It's a hundred years before

03:39.950 --> 03:43.370
people can read the EDI files.

03:44.650 --> 03:48.810
I looked at them. But I don't need to read

03:48.810 --> 03:54.090
the files, I said. I can get the stories from

03:54.090 --> 03:54.430
you.

03:55.730 --> 03:59.370
And I did. Here are some of them.

04:16.510 --> 04:22.890
Omega File 349. London, England.

04:24.870 --> 04:30.750
There's a young man in London called Johnny Cook.

04:31.750 --> 04:38.990
Hawker said. He's about 18. He doesn't have a home,

04:40.050 --> 04:43.690
but he goes clubbing nearly every night.

04:44.690 --> 04:49.410
Those all night dance clubs for young people.

04:50.970 --> 04:54.030
Here's a photograph of him.

04:55.330 --> 05:00.770
He put the photograph on the table, and Jude and

05:00.770 --> 05:02.430
Hawker looked at it.

05:03.650 --> 05:10.610
And Hawker said, he wants to sell a story to

05:10.610 --> 05:13.090
a newspaper, Arla said.

05:14.130 --> 05:21.790
Some story about a drug company. Find him. Talk to

05:21.790 --> 05:27.310
him. What's his story? I want to know.

05:28.750 --> 05:34.350
Jude and Hawker took an afternoon plane from Brussels to

05:34.350 --> 05:37.690
London, and then went to a hotel.

05:39.790 --> 05:47.110
What are you going to wear tonight? Said Jude. Not

05:47.110 --> 05:49.250
those old jeans, please.

05:50.710 --> 05:56.670
What's wrong with them? Hawker said. We're going clubbing. Not

05:56.670 --> 05:58.670
out to dinner at the Ritz hotel.

05:59.730 --> 06:05.670
Well, wear a different shirt then. That one's dirty.

06:06.630 --> 06:11.610
You can wash it for me, Hawker said. Get lost,

06:12.230 --> 06:13.070
said Jude.

06:14.010 --> 06:18.290
They had dinner, watched television for an hour or two,

06:19.010 --> 06:20.530
and then went out.

06:22.210 --> 06:26.150
It was a warm night with a little rain now

06:26.150 --> 06:26.470
and then.

06:27.670 --> 06:30.690
London weather, said Hawker.

06:31.890 --> 06:36.650
They found a taxi with a young driver and got

06:36.650 --> 06:36.910
in.

06:37.910 --> 06:40.410
We're two, said the driver.

06:41.410 --> 06:44.690
We want to go clubbing, Jude said.

06:45.630 --> 06:49.810
Where's the best place this week? Do you know?

06:50.710 --> 06:53.590
Brew nose, the driver said.

06:54.850 --> 07:00.750
Or Garcia's, down by the river. Everybody's going there this

07:00.750 --> 07:01.050
week.

07:01.970 --> 07:05.710
Okay. Let's go, said Hawker.

07:06.910 --> 07:11.710
They went to Garcia's first, then moved on to Brew

07:11.710 --> 07:11.930
nose.

07:13.070 --> 07:18.610
They found Johnny Cook in a third club, called Montes.

07:19.350 --> 07:21.670
It was two o'clock in the morning.

07:23.070 --> 07:27.630
That's him all right, Hawker said. Look at his ear.

07:28.630 --> 07:34.290
Johnny Cook was tall and thin with long yellow hair

07:34.290 --> 07:38.090
and two black earrings in his left ear.

07:39.750 --> 07:45.350
Johnny, Johnny Cook shouted Jude suddenly.

07:46.290 --> 07:50.770
She ran and put her arms around Johnny Cook's neck.

07:51.770 --> 07:55.230
Hi, Johnny. You remember me?

07:56.010 --> 08:00.250
Jude, we met last week at Garcia's.

08:00.690 --> 08:05.690
You remember? Oh, this is my friend, Hawker.

08:06.230 --> 08:10.430
Hi, Johnny. Good to meet you, said Hawker.

08:11.230 --> 08:15.790
Hi, said Johnny Cook. He looked at Jude.

08:16.790 --> 08:19.010
Did we meet at Garcia's?

08:19.630 --> 08:25.170
Of course we did, laughed Jude. I was with Sara

08:25.170 --> 08:27.130
and Patty and the others.

08:27.750 --> 08:33.970
Remember? Oh, yeah, said Johnny. I remember.

08:34.910 --> 08:38.170
He looked around. Are they here tonight?

08:39.070 --> 08:43.650
No, it's just me and Hawker tonight, said Jude.

08:44.650 --> 08:46.550
Come on. Let's dance.

08:48.950 --> 08:52.910
They danced for two hours. Then they left with about

08:52.910 --> 08:56.830
ten other people and went across the river to a

08:56.830 --> 08:57.310
new club.

08:58.610 --> 09:03.410
The music there was louder and the dancing was very

09:03.410 --> 09:03.850
fast.

09:05.130 --> 09:10.110
After two more hours of dancing, Hawker was hot, tired

09:10.110 --> 09:11.410
and thirsty.

09:12.710 --> 09:17.610
I'm getting old, he said to Jude. Don't these people

09:17.610 --> 09:18.790
ever go to bed?

09:19.830 --> 09:25.470
Your only twenty-five said Jude. That's not old, and

09:25.470 --> 09:26.710
you can't stop yet.

09:27.670 --> 09:31.550
He's getting very friendly now, and we can take him

09:31.550 --> 09:32.790
to breakfast soon.

09:33.670 --> 09:39.030
At seven o'clock, the club closed, and Jude and

09:39.030 --> 09:42.070
Hawker took Johnny back to their hotel.

09:43.110 --> 09:47.610
Jude picked up the phone and asked for three big

09:47.610 --> 09:49.370
breakfasts in the room.

09:50.670 --> 09:57.050
Hawker took his shoes off. Ah, that's better, he said.

09:58.110 --> 09:59.370
He looked at Johnny.

10:00.750 --> 10:05.310
How often do you go clubbing, Johnny? And what do

10:05.310 --> 10:06.250
you do in the daytime?

10:07.490 --> 10:12.830
Not a lot. Sleep, usually. I go clubbing most nights.

10:14.030 --> 10:16.550
Where do you live? Hawker asked.

10:17.550 --> 10:22.750
On the streets, said Johnny. When I'm rich, I'm going

10:22.750 --> 10:24.850
to get a boat and live on that.

10:25.950 --> 10:32.690
Rich, Jude said. Oh yes, we all want to be

10:32.690 --> 10:33.150
rich.

10:34.330 --> 10:39.350
But I am going to be rich, Johnny said.

10:40.130 --> 10:45.310
I've got a good story. See? He laughed.

10:46.190 --> 10:51.950
I'm going to sell it. A newspaper wants to give

10:51.950 --> 10:56.970
me 100,000 euros for it.

10:58.090 --> 11:02.550
They gave me 1,000 last month, and I'm going

11:02.550 --> 11:07.090
to get the other 99,000 very soon.

11:08.190 --> 11:10.490
Great, said Jude.

11:12.030 --> 11:17.710
So, what's the story then, Johnny? Have some more coffee

11:17.710 --> 11:20.370
and tell us all about it.

11:22.010 --> 11:27.410
Well, you know the Tyler drug company? Johnny began.

11:28.310 --> 11:30.850
They make drugs and medicines.

11:31.950 --> 11:38.150
Yes, Hawker said. It's a very big European company. They've

11:38.150 --> 11:40.390
got offices in all the big cities.

11:41.070 --> 11:44.650
Yeah, that's right, Johnny said.

11:45.290 --> 11:51.250
Well, they're taking young people off the streets and using

11:51.250 --> 11:52.850
them for tests.

11:53.850 --> 11:55.030
Jude laughed.

11:56.270 --> 11:59.850
Nobody's going to believe that, she said.

12:01.010 --> 12:06.070
Drug companies use animals, not people, for their tests.

12:07.210 --> 12:10.930
Some new drugs can be very dangerous at first.

12:12.050 --> 12:15.690
Nobody wants people to die from a new medicine.

12:16.970 --> 12:20.930
It's true, Johnny said, angrily.

12:21.810 --> 12:23.150
Think about it.

12:24.250 --> 12:28.030
All those young, homeless people in London.

12:29.090 --> 12:33.730
They sleep every night along the Strand and other streets.

12:34.790 --> 12:40.210
Nobody wants to know them. Nobody asks questions about them.

12:40.950 --> 12:45.370
They've got no home, no family, nothing.

12:46.310 --> 12:50.510
But they've got legs, Hawker said. They can run away.

12:51.470 --> 12:55.490
You don't understand, said Johnny.

12:56.130 --> 13:02.190
Listen, I know because I was there.

13:03.190 --> 13:05.690
I live on the streets, right?

13:06.530 --> 13:12.110
And late one night, along the Strand, they came and

13:12.110 --> 13:14.130
took me and some other people.

13:14.950 --> 13:16.750
A boy and two girls.

13:17.570 --> 13:20.770
They wanted to help us, they said.

13:21.710 --> 13:26.770
Hot food, nice beds, new clothes, everything.

13:27.710 --> 13:31.090
They took us to this big house.

13:32.050 --> 13:34.170
Where? said Hawker.

13:34.950 --> 13:38.510
I'm not saying where? said Johnny.

13:39.390 --> 13:42.350
And what happened? asked Jude.

13:43.390 --> 13:48.850
They gave us food and new clothes and beds to

13:48.850 --> 13:50.150
sleep in, all right?

13:51.250 --> 13:53.790
But we couldn't get out of the house.

13:54.790 --> 13:59.410
And men in white coats watched us all the time.

14:00.370 --> 14:03.250
And they put drugs in our food.

14:04.290 --> 14:07.190
How do you know that? Hawker asked.

14:08.270 --> 14:09.510
I felt ill.

14:10.530 --> 14:15.330
My eyes went strange and I couldn't see very well.

14:16.410 --> 14:21.270
And one of the girls, she got very ill one

14:21.270 --> 14:21.670
night.

14:22.540 --> 14:24.590
She screamed and screamed.

14:25.750 --> 14:27.690
And the men in white coats came.

14:28.990 --> 14:33.070
I was in the next room and I listened through

14:33.070 --> 14:33.610
the wall.

14:34.590 --> 14:39.210
This is very strange, one of the men said.

14:39.950 --> 14:45.050
She had 20 grams of coplast in her dinner tonight.

14:46.270 --> 14:48.750
Was that too much, do you think?

14:49.990 --> 14:53.010
I don't know, said a second man.

14:53.950 --> 14:55.610
We don't want to kill her.

14:56.530 --> 15:03.110
Let's try 20 grams again tomorrow on this girl and

15:03.110 --> 15:04.130
on one of the boys.

15:04.850 --> 15:07.530
We can't stop this test now.

15:08.190 --> 15:10.790
We must get answers quickly.

15:12.470 --> 15:17.770
After that, they talked more quietly and I couldn't hear.

15:18.770 --> 15:22.710
But I didn't eat any more food in that house.

15:23.650 --> 15:27.670
And the next night I got into an office downstairs

15:27.670 --> 15:30.290
and took some papers.

15:31.310 --> 15:35.670
Then I broke out of the house and ran away

15:35.670 --> 15:36.570
fast.

15:37.610 --> 15:40.270
What papers, said Hawker?

15:41.210 --> 15:46.010
Papers with Tyler drug company's name on them.

15:46.010 --> 15:50.530
And where are those papers now?

15:51.370 --> 15:52.050
Asked Jude.

15:53.230 --> 15:56.910
That's my secret, Johnny said.

15:57.690 --> 16:02.310
When the newspaper gives me the money, I'm going to

16:02.310 --> 16:03.030
tell them.

16:03.770 --> 16:06.430
But I'm not going to tell you.

16:08.900 --> 16:13.250
The next day, Jude and Hawker flew back to Brussels

16:13.250 --> 16:15.810
and went to Arla's office.

16:17.210 --> 16:21.730
Arla listened to Johnny Cook's story, but he didn't say

16:21.730 --> 16:22.170
anything.

16:24.130 --> 16:27.810
So, what do we do now, Jude said?

16:28.610 --> 16:30.990
Do we look for this big house?

16:31.630 --> 16:33.890
And Arla picked up his telephone.

16:34.950 --> 16:37.650
Come back in an hour, he said.

16:38.670 --> 16:40.650
Get a coffee or something.

16:41.850 --> 16:46.650
An hour and three coffees later, they went back.

16:47.650 --> 16:50.130
Okay, said Arla.

16:50.930 --> 16:53.990
You can forget all about this.

16:54.970 --> 16:58.030
Cook's story isn't true.

16:59.490 --> 17:01.370
Jude stared at him.

17:01.930 --> 17:03.870
Who told you that?

17:04.670 --> 17:05.030
She said.

17:06.030 --> 17:10.250
I want to talk to Johnny Cook again, Hawker said.

17:10.950 --> 17:13.790
You can't, said Arla.

17:14.750 --> 17:15.990
He's dead.

17:17.530 --> 17:21.470
Hawker looked at Jude and then back at Arla.

17:22.330 --> 17:26.170
He was alive yesterday, said Hawker.

17:26.990 --> 17:30.450
Well, he isn't alive today.

17:31.450 --> 17:35.210
He came out of a club at three o'clock

17:35.210 --> 17:36.090
this morning

17:36.090 --> 17:39.570
and fell in the river Thames.

17:40.890 --> 17:44.270
When they got him out, he was dead.

17:45.430 --> 17:49.550
But, Jude began, forget it, Jude.

17:50.530 --> 17:52.850
The file is closed.

17:55.210 --> 17:58.290
And was that the end of it?

17:59.130 --> 18:03.350
I asked when Jude and Hawker finished telling the story.

18:04.130 --> 18:06.310
Yes, said Hawker.

18:06.950 --> 18:09.770
Arla never spoke about it again.

18:11.230 --> 18:16.110
And did you believe Johnny's story about the drug company?

18:16.870 --> 18:17.470
I asked.

18:18.750 --> 18:22.930
Before a company can sell a new medicine to people,

18:23.350 --> 18:24.230
said Hawker,

18:25.030 --> 18:27.830
there are years and years of tests.

18:28.730 --> 18:32.730
They do the tests on animals, of course,

18:33.770 --> 18:39.690
but they learn much more quickly from tests on people.

18:40.690 --> 18:43.270
There are lots of drug companies,

18:43.270 --> 18:48.710
and every company wants to be the first with a

18:48.710 --> 18:49.450
new medicine.

18:51.030 --> 18:54.870
About five years later, Jude said,

18:55.890 --> 19:00.310
the Tyler drug company began to sell a new drug

19:00.310 --> 19:02.870
called Coplastin.

19:03.370 --> 19:06.670
It was a medicine to stop some kinds of cancer.

19:07.570 --> 19:08.490
And it worked.

19:09.430 --> 19:10.890
Everybody wanted it.

19:10.890 --> 19:13.950
The company made a lot of money,

19:14.710 --> 19:18.170
and so the government got a lot of money from

19:18.170 --> 19:20.410
the company in taxes.

19:21.610 --> 19:27.030
Governments like rich companies and big fat taxes,

19:27.750 --> 19:33.690
they're not very interested in homeless young people sleeping on

19:33.690 --> 19:34.190
the streets.

19:35.810 --> 19:40.550
So, Johnny Cook's story was true, I said,

19:41.290 --> 19:44.290
and he didn't fall into the river.

19:45.450 --> 19:47.530
Somebody pushed him.

19:48.390 --> 19:52.490
Of course they pushed him, said Jude.

19:53.730 --> 19:55.770
Dead men can't talk.

19:57.070 --> 19:57.490
Can they?

20:15.310 --> 20:18.590
Omega File 451

20:19.950 --> 20:22.330
Loch Ness, Scotland

20:24.770 --> 20:29.290
I want you to take the next plane to Scotland,

20:29.370 --> 20:31.030
said Arla,

20:31.030 --> 20:34.970
then get up to Loch Ness.

20:35.770 --> 20:38.170
Oh, great, said Hawker.

20:38.910 --> 20:41.030
Are we looking for the Loch Ness monster?

20:42.110 --> 20:43.170
Old Nessie?

20:44.130 --> 20:44.890
Jude laughed.

20:45.890 --> 20:48.370
Don't laugh, said Arla.

20:49.190 --> 20:52.070
You are looking for a monster.

20:53.130 --> 20:55.910
Oh, come on, Arla, Jude said.

20:56.490 --> 20:58.110
You don't mean that.

20:58.110 --> 21:06.290
This photo came by email from Edinburgh, said Arla.

21:07.270 --> 21:07.730
Look.

21:08.770 --> 21:12.270
He turned to his computer and opened a file.

21:13.190 --> 21:18.190
It's a nighttime photo and not very good.

21:19.970 --> 21:23.990
Hawker and Jude stared at the photo on the computer

21:23.990 --> 21:24.450
screen.

21:24.450 --> 21:31.650
They could see water and something big and grey, half

21:31.650 --> 21:34.390
in and half out of the water.

21:36.030 --> 21:40.730
It's got arms and a head, said Hawker.

21:41.570 --> 21:43.310
But what is it?

21:44.590 --> 21:50.790
It kills sheep, cats and dogs, Arla said.

21:50.790 --> 21:55.330
And perhaps small children next.

21:56.650 --> 22:01.430
People in Fort Augustus are screaming at London,

22:02.090 --> 22:05.570
and London is screaming at us.

22:07.070 --> 22:08.950
Go and find it.

22:09.670 --> 22:14.070
What do we do with it when we find it,

22:14.570 --> 22:15.290
asked Jude?

22:15.290 --> 22:22.710
Kill it, said Arla, before it kills you.

22:24.730 --> 22:29.430
Hawker and Jude waited for a minute, but Arla turned

22:29.430 --> 22:32.630
away and began to read his emails.

22:34.530 --> 22:38.870
Are you telling us everything, Arla, asked Hawker?

22:39.590 --> 22:40.910
Of course.

22:42.190 --> 22:44.750
Arla put his hands on the table.

22:45.730 --> 22:49.070
There were only two fingers on his left hand.

22:50.070 --> 22:53.330
I always tell you everything.

22:54.430 --> 22:55.810
You know that.

22:56.810 --> 22:58.990
Ha, said Jude.

23:00.870 --> 23:07.030
They took a plane to Inverness, then drove along the

23:07.030 --> 23:10.390
side of Loch Ness to Fort Augustus.

23:11.010 --> 23:18.490
It was a grey November day, grey sky, grey water,

23:19.130 --> 23:20.510
grey hills.

23:21.830 --> 23:25.010
Hawker looked across the lock.

23:26.290 --> 23:30.870
It's easy to believe in monsters here, he said.

23:31.870 --> 23:39.270
Loch Ness is about 200 meters deep, the third deepest

23:39.270 --> 23:40.890
lake in Europe.

23:42.130 --> 23:43.350
Did you know that?

23:44.530 --> 23:47.270
A hundred monsters could live down there.

23:48.890 --> 23:53.890
How are we going to find this thing, asked Jude?

23:54.830 --> 24:00.030
Talk to people in Fort Augustus first, Hawker said.

24:01.350 --> 24:03.110
Then take it from there.

24:04.510 --> 24:09.530
They talked to people in their hotel, and to people

24:09.530 --> 24:11.750
in the streets in Fort Augustus.

24:13.150 --> 24:15.790
Everybody had a lot to say.

24:16.790 --> 24:23.210
It killed Mrs. Fraser's dog, said one woman.

24:23.730 --> 24:28.270
She has a house down by the water.

24:29.190 --> 24:34.190
The monster came into her garden one night.

24:35.330 --> 24:41.750
Her little dog went to look, and the monster killed

24:41.750 --> 24:44.670
him just like that.

24:46.050 --> 24:52.330
Killed six of my brother's sheep, said a man called

24:52.330 --> 24:52.970
Dougal.

24:53.730 --> 24:57.290
He's very angry about it.

24:58.530 --> 25:00.930
Can we meet your brother?

25:01.650 --> 25:02.210
Asked Jude.

25:03.110 --> 25:05.070
Ask him some questions.

25:07.050 --> 25:14.630
Dougal's brother, Archie, lived in the Morriston, about nine kilometers

25:14.630 --> 25:15.870
up the lock.

25:16.830 --> 25:21.650
He was a big man with black hair and blue

25:21.650 --> 25:22.190
eyes.

25:23.310 --> 25:26.530
He was not very friendly at first.

25:27.530 --> 25:29.610
Who are you?

25:30.370 --> 25:30.850
He asked.

25:32.030 --> 25:34.610
Are you army people?

25:35.290 --> 25:37.390
No, said Hawker.

25:38.190 --> 25:40.090
Why do you ask that?

25:41.090 --> 25:47.270
There's an army laboratory in the hills above the lock.

25:48.470 --> 25:54.470
Lots of strange people there, and lots of boats on

25:54.470 --> 25:55.970
the lock at night.

25:55.970 --> 25:58.690
Coming and going.

25:59.790 --> 26:03.470
Hmm, interesting, said Jude.

26:04.690 --> 26:10.170
But tell us about the lockness monster, and your dead

26:10.170 --> 26:10.610
sheep.

26:11.450 --> 26:14.310
It wasn't Nessie.

26:15.070 --> 26:19.650
Nessie doesn't kill sheep, Archie said.

26:20.330 --> 26:25.390
This thing broke their necks.

26:26.590 --> 26:30.010
Did you see it, asked Hawker?

26:30.930 --> 26:38.170
Well, I saw something big, but it moved very fast.

26:39.050 --> 26:44.350
It was back in the lock in seconds, and it

26:44.350 --> 26:46.230
was nearly dark.

26:47.230 --> 26:49.710
Right, said Hawker.

26:50.570 --> 26:55.730
Now, we'd like to look at your dead sheep, please,

26:56.710 --> 26:59.670
and then we need a boat.

27:00.590 --> 27:04.630
Where can we get a fast boat, Archie?

27:05.610 --> 27:08.710
What do you want a boat for?

27:09.810 --> 27:15.790
We're going to catch this thing, said Jude, and stop

27:15.790 --> 27:17.670
it, killing your sheep.

27:19.690 --> 27:25.370
For the next four days, Hawker and Jude went up

27:25.370 --> 27:29.930
and down lock Ness in Archie Campbell's boat.

27:31.090 --> 27:34.350
They talked to everybody around the lock.

27:35.750 --> 27:39.510
When you see this monster, please ring us.

27:40.310 --> 27:46.310
Anytime, day or night, our mobile phones are always turned

27:46.310 --> 27:46.810
on.

27:48.450 --> 27:52.530
They slept a little in the day, and were out

27:52.530 --> 27:56.450
most of the night in the boat, with their guns,

27:56.450 --> 28:04.030
cameras, mobile phones, a big flashlight, and liters of hot

28:04.030 --> 28:04.410
coffee.

28:06.290 --> 28:11.850
Once, they thought they saw the monster just north of

28:11.850 --> 28:12.750
Inver Morriston.

28:14.090 --> 28:19.110
Another night, a call came from a little place called

28:19.110 --> 28:19.950
Foyers.

28:21.050 --> 28:24.210
They got there at six in the morning.

28:24.210 --> 28:30.790
It was dark and cold, and everything was very quiet.

28:31.810 --> 28:36.370
They sat in the boat, looking up and down the

28:36.370 --> 28:36.590
lock.

28:38.130 --> 28:44.450
Lock whispered Hawker, down there, by the trees.

28:46.190 --> 28:51.970
Fifty meters away, there were some tall trees by the

28:51.970 --> 28:52.890
side of the lock.

28:53.770 --> 28:59.330
There were some sheep under the trees, and something big

28:59.330 --> 29:00.610
and dark.

29:02.030 --> 29:05.930
Suddenly, the sheep began to run.

29:06.930 --> 29:10.010
Start the engine, said Hawker.

29:10.850 --> 29:12.590
Let's get down there.

29:13.970 --> 29:19.030
When they got to the trees, they found five sheep

29:19.030 --> 29:23.210
with broken necks, but no monster.

29:24.430 --> 29:30.470
It just kills and goes away again, said Jude.

29:31.450 --> 29:32.330
Horrible.

29:33.890 --> 29:40.050
The next night, they were near Erkut Castle, when they

29:40.050 --> 29:41.650
saw two other boats.

29:42.710 --> 29:45.230
It was three in the morning.

29:46.310 --> 29:49.870
Those boats again, said Hawker.

29:50.790 --> 29:55.470
We heard their engines last night, and the night before.

29:56.370 --> 29:57.530
Who are they?

29:58.390 --> 30:00.070
Let's go and see.

30:01.750 --> 30:05.030
Quietly, their boat moved nearer.

30:06.070 --> 30:09.170
There were four men in each boat.

30:10.130 --> 30:14.570
Men in grey, young men with hard faces.

30:15.750 --> 30:20.350
They watched Hawker and Jude, and said nothing.

30:21.490 --> 30:25.530
Hello, said Jude, with a friendly smile.

30:26.950 --> 30:27.810
Who are you?

30:29.010 --> 30:32.570
A tall man in the nearest boat answered.

30:33.750 --> 30:35.750
Army, he said.

30:36.590 --> 30:37.630
Who are you?

30:38.450 --> 30:42.730
What are you doing out here at this time of

30:42.730 --> 30:43.050
night?

30:44.250 --> 30:49.870
Where visitors, said Jude, looking for Nessie, of course.

30:50.950 --> 30:52.610
What are you doing?

30:54.230 --> 30:59.010
There's no monster in this lock, said the tall man.

30:59.890 --> 31:04.230
Go back to your hotel and go to bed.

31:05.410 --> 31:09.190
The two army boats moved away down the lock.

31:10.350 --> 31:12.630
Nice, said Hawker.

31:13.810 --> 31:14.890
Very friendly.

31:17.170 --> 31:19.750
Allah phoned them every morning.

31:20.730 --> 31:23.210
Get on with it, he said.

31:23.210 --> 31:27.170
Before this thing kills someone.

31:28.510 --> 31:32.770
We can't get near it, Jude told him.

31:33.370 --> 31:40.830
This lock is 36 kilometers long and two kilometers across.

31:41.630 --> 31:46.010
There are only two of us, and we're not getting

31:46.010 --> 31:46.910
any sleep.

31:47.910 --> 31:51.890
You can sleep later, said Allah.

31:52.750 --> 31:55.370
Just catch this thing.

31:56.590 --> 32:01.610
We met some army people last night, Jude said.

32:02.790 --> 32:04.430
What are they doing here?

32:05.610 --> 32:07.990
What do they do at their laboratory?

32:09.490 --> 32:14.450
The phone went quiet, then what laboratory?

32:15.670 --> 32:20.690
The army laboratory in the hills above lock Ness.

32:21.830 --> 32:23.310
The phone went dead.

32:24.470 --> 32:28.050
Well, well, Jude said to Hawker.

32:29.010 --> 32:33.210
He doesn't know, or he's not telling.

32:35.110 --> 32:39.890
The monster came out of the lock and killed sheep

32:39.890 --> 32:42.070
nearly every night.

32:43.070 --> 32:48.470
Everybody around the lock wanted to help Hawker and Jude,

32:49.110 --> 32:52.670
and their mobile phones never stopped ringing.

32:53.770 --> 32:58.850
A lot of people thought the monster was Nessie,

32:59.370 --> 33:02.290
but Archie knew it wasn't.

33:03.270 --> 33:10.570
Nessie never killed anything in fifteen hundred years.

33:10.570 --> 33:15.230
He said, this is something different,

33:16.310 --> 33:20.730
and it's going to start killing people soon.

33:21.870 --> 33:24.750
Look, you need some sheep.

33:25.890 --> 33:28.270
Sheep, said Hawker.

33:29.170 --> 33:30.770
Do you mean sleep?

33:31.850 --> 33:35.550
He was very tired after ten nights on the lock.

33:35.550 --> 33:41.450
Of course, said Jude, clever Archie.

33:42.270 --> 33:45.430
Can you get us some old sheep, then?

33:46.070 --> 33:48.530
Or perhaps we can use Hawker.

33:49.310 --> 33:52.010
He's nearly an old sheep by now.

33:52.850 --> 33:55.750
Oh, shut up, said Hawker.

33:57.010 --> 34:02.090
They found a good place between in the Morriston and

34:02.090 --> 34:02.810
Erkut Castle,

34:02.810 --> 34:08.090
with some trees by the water, and took their six

34:08.090 --> 34:09.490
old sheep there.

34:10.430 --> 34:15.230
For three nights they watched, but no monster came.

34:16.650 --> 34:20.310
The men in grey were out every night, too.

34:21.090 --> 34:26.330
They were never far away from Hawker and Jude, but

34:26.330 --> 34:27.950
never came to speak to them.

34:29.450 --> 34:34.670
On the fourth night, Hawker and Jude arrived at their

34:34.670 --> 34:37.190
sheep place later than usual.

34:38.670 --> 34:44.230
It was a warm, rainy night, soft Scottish rain that

34:44.230 --> 34:45.070
never stops.

34:46.750 --> 34:51.430
When they turned the engine off, everything was quiet.

34:52.710 --> 34:55.570
Just the rain whispering on the lock.

34:57.010 --> 35:00.970
Hawker got out of the boat and stood with the

35:00.970 --> 35:04.550
flashlight, watching and listening.

35:05.810 --> 35:09.610
Jude sat in the boat with her gun in her

35:09.610 --> 35:09.950
hand.

35:11.030 --> 35:16.110
Where are the men in grey, whispered Hawker?

35:17.410 --> 35:20.910
Don't know, Jude whispered back.

35:21.910 --> 35:24.250
Behind us, I think.

35:26.110 --> 35:29.650
Then everything happened at once.

35:30.830 --> 35:35.230
There was a sudden noise of boats' engines behind them,

35:36.170 --> 35:40.370
and at the same time, something moved in the water

35:40.370 --> 35:41.830
in front of them.

35:42.790 --> 35:48.610
Ahead, and two long arms came out of the water.

35:48.610 --> 35:51.750
Light shouted Jude.

35:52.590 --> 35:52.970
Quick!

35:54.290 --> 36:00.150
Hawker turned on the flashlight, and at once the monster

36:00.150 --> 36:04.750
stood up and ran at Hawker through the water,

36:05.670 --> 36:09.130
its long arms going for Hawker's head.

36:10.130 --> 36:12.290
Get down, Hawker!

36:13.250 --> 36:14.490
Screamed Jude.

36:15.730 --> 36:21.850
In a second, Hawker was under the water, and then

36:21.850 --> 36:29.390
came the sound of Jude's gun, once, twice, and then

36:29.390 --> 36:30.430
a third time.

36:32.510 --> 36:38.710
When the monster stopped moving, Hawker and Jude went to

36:38.710 --> 36:39.390
look at it.

36:39.890 --> 36:46.010
It was a greeny black color, bigger than a man,

36:47.030 --> 36:50.430
and with very long arms and legs.

36:51.090 --> 36:55.510
It had a small head on a long neck.

36:56.570 --> 36:59.970
It was a strange, horrible thing.

37:01.070 --> 37:07.110
A minute later, the men in grey arrived in their

37:07.110 --> 37:07.790
two boats.

37:08.850 --> 37:13.270
They got out and came to look at the dead

37:13.270 --> 37:13.590
monster.

37:14.790 --> 37:21.730
Oh dear, the tall man said, poor old Nessie.

37:22.770 --> 37:27.710
That, said Hawker, is not Nessie.

37:28.650 --> 37:30.710
So what is it?

37:31.950 --> 37:36.230
Visitors, aren't you, said the tall man?

37:37.190 --> 37:38.430
Where from?

37:40.190 --> 37:44.810
Hawker and Jude stared at him and said nothing.

37:46.850 --> 37:51.910
Then Jude took something out of her pocket and held

37:51.910 --> 37:55.410
it up, in front of the tall man's eyes.

37:56.910 --> 37:58.250
He looked at it.

37:59.250 --> 38:06.110
Oh, he said, I see, E-D-I.

38:07.430 --> 38:09.370
Don't see many of those.

38:10.670 --> 38:15.110
Okay, what do you want to know?

38:16.450 --> 38:22.930
What is that thing, said Jude?

38:23.930 --> 38:26.810
The tall man looked unhappy.

38:28.290 --> 38:35.010
It is, or it was, one of the army's new

38:35.010 --> 38:35.670
fighters.

38:36.710 --> 38:42.390
It got away from our laboratory, and we just couldn't

38:42.390 --> 38:43.170
catch it.

38:44.170 --> 38:52.010
But it was alive, a living thing, said Hawker.

38:53.070 --> 38:56.770
You can make a lot of living things in a

38:56.770 --> 39:00.370
laboratory these days, said the tall man.

39:02.270 --> 39:05.690
Genetic engineering is getting very clever.

39:06.690 --> 39:14.390
This fighter can run all night, live underwater, see in

39:14.390 --> 39:14.930
the dark.

39:15.930 --> 39:17.150
But it's new.

39:18.270 --> 39:20.790
We haven't got it right yet.

39:22.010 --> 39:27.450
And it's programmed to kill anything, is it?

39:28.050 --> 39:28.610
Said Jude.

39:29.350 --> 39:33.470
No, no, the tall man said, quickly.

39:33.470 --> 39:36.010
Not this one.

39:36.850 --> 39:43.610
This one just kills small animals with four legs, sheep,

39:44.310 --> 39:47.590
dogs, cats, things like that.

39:48.530 --> 39:53.170
Well, said Jude, that is nice to know.

39:54.830 --> 40:00.290
And where are the other monsters, asked Hawker, for killing

40:00.290 --> 40:03.110
men, women, and children?

40:04.310 --> 40:05.730
Things like that.

40:07.110 --> 40:08.550
The tall man smiled.

40:10.110 --> 40:12.970
Can't answer that, I'm afraid.

40:14.230 --> 40:16.550
Talk to your people in Brussels.

40:17.830 --> 40:20.790
Well, we must get back.

40:21.650 --> 40:23.430
Lots to do, you know.

40:24.530 --> 40:26.190
Thanks for your help.

40:27.350 --> 40:28.090
Bye.

40:29.670 --> 40:34.070
The men in grey put their dead monster in one

40:34.070 --> 40:38.490
of the boats, and went away up the lock, into

40:38.490 --> 40:40.650
the dark, and the rain.

40:44.070 --> 40:48.370
And what did Arla say about it all, I asked?

40:49.430 --> 40:53.110
He was so angry, Hawker said.

40:53.770 --> 40:55.030
He went crazy.

40:56.910 --> 41:00.090
He didn't know about the monsters, you see.

41:01.130 --> 41:02.190
All the laboratory.

41:03.230 --> 41:07.630
The army didn't tell anyone in Brussels.

41:08.810 --> 41:15.350
And Arla liked to know everyone's secrets, said Jude.

41:16.390 --> 41:20.350
Did the army make any more monsters?

41:21.230 --> 41:21.770
I asked.

41:22.250 --> 41:26.430
Not in Scotland, said Hawker.

41:27.430 --> 41:31.630
The British army closed their laboratory after that.

41:31.630 --> 41:38.210
The Americans and the French made some monsters years later.

41:39.130 --> 41:45.530
They were smaller, like big cats, but with eight legs.

41:46.830 --> 41:49.650
Where are they now, I said?

41:50.250 --> 41:52.730
You don't hear anything about them?

41:53.570 --> 41:57.010
Of course not, said Jude.

41:57.870 --> 42:02.050
People don't want to hear about monsters.

42:04.010 --> 42:09.710
They're in Antarctica, or in a place deep under the

42:09.710 --> 42:11.570
ground, said Hawker.

42:12.330 --> 42:18.310
Nice and secret, just waiting for the next war.

42:19.850 --> 42:26.590
And so there isn't a Loch Ness monster, and never

42:26.590 --> 42:28.810
was one, I said.

42:30.350 --> 42:36.610
Nessie, said Jude, she looked me in the eyes and

42:36.610 --> 42:37.650
did not smile.

42:38.530 --> 42:41.810
Of course there's a Loch Ness monster.

42:42.970 --> 42:45.670
She's a blue, grey colour.

42:46.750 --> 42:51.950
Has a small head, a very long neck, and is

42:51.950 --> 42:54.730
about 15 metres long.

42:56.050 --> 43:00.190
Go and look at all the photos of her on

43:00.190 --> 43:00.770
the internet.

43:18.150 --> 43:21.470
Omega File 522

43:22.790 --> 43:25.630
Galapagos, Ecuador.

43:27.230 --> 43:29.870
Got your son hats?

43:30.950 --> 43:31.570
Said Allah.

43:32.590 --> 43:33.510
Why?

43:34.710 --> 43:34.950
Asked Jude.

43:35.890 --> 43:37.570
Where are we going now?

43:37.570 --> 43:42.050
South America, Allah said.

43:43.290 --> 43:45.590
Big place, said Jude.

43:46.810 --> 43:47.850
How about Chile?

43:48.850 --> 43:49.990
I like Chile.

43:51.070 --> 43:53.310
No, it's Ecuador.

43:54.550 --> 44:00.730
You're going to the Galapagos Islands, a thousand kilometres out

44:00.730 --> 44:02.370
in the Pacific Ocean.

44:03.370 --> 44:06.510
Oh, right, Hawker said.

44:07.490 --> 44:09.910
Are you going to tell us why?

44:11.010 --> 44:13.070
Allah looked unhappy.

44:14.070 --> 44:18.430
There's something strange going on.

44:19.430 --> 44:25.870
EDI is getting emails every day from the Galapagos.

44:26.750 --> 44:30.410
They're all about Isabella Island.

44:30.410 --> 44:35.150
And they all say things like this.

44:36.530 --> 44:40.030
He gave Hawker and Jude a piece of paper.

44:41.710 --> 44:45.030
Important news, important news.

44:45.890 --> 44:49.850
A new time is coming for our planet.

44:51.230 --> 44:58.010
The first visitors are now on Isabella Island, Galapagos.

44:59.270 --> 45:00.610
Don't fight them.

45:01.570 --> 45:03.250
Don't be afraid of them.

45:04.130 --> 45:05.290
Be friendly.

45:06.630 --> 45:09.410
Tell your government now.

45:11.230 --> 45:15.190
Hawker and Jude looked at Allah and then laughed.

45:16.570 --> 45:20.530
There are a lot of crazy people out there on

45:20.530 --> 45:22.330
the internet, said Jude.

45:22.330 --> 45:25.410
You don't believe this one?

45:26.210 --> 45:26.750
Do you?

45:27.930 --> 45:29.390
Perhaps it's crazy.

45:30.490 --> 45:33.890
And perhaps it's not, said Allah.

45:35.130 --> 45:40.810
But when we email back with questions, they don't answer.

45:41.930 --> 45:48.550
The Americans are watching the island by satellite, but they

45:48.550 --> 45:50.670
don't want to tell us why.

45:51.670 --> 45:56.310
There are two Australian ships going there.

45:57.310 --> 46:00.790
The Mexicans are getting very excited.

46:02.130 --> 46:05.830
And the Ecuadorians are saying nothing.

46:07.010 --> 46:10.170
Something is happening on Isabella.

46:11.190 --> 46:12.610
What is it?

46:13.590 --> 46:15.390
We want to know.

46:17.790 --> 46:23.650
From Brussels to the Galapagos is a long way.

46:23.710 --> 46:27.230
Hawker and Jude took a plane to Cuba.

46:28.490 --> 46:30.410
A second plane to Ecuador.

46:31.890 --> 46:36.410
Then a third plane out to Bultra Island in the

46:36.410 --> 46:36.930
Galapagos.

46:38.210 --> 46:42.090
When they got out of the plane, a wall of

46:42.090 --> 46:43.630
hot air hit them.

46:44.550 --> 46:46.910
Oh, said Hawker.

46:47.730 --> 46:49.450
He put on his son hat quickly.

46:51.250 --> 46:56.150
They went across to Santa Cruz Island and down to

46:56.150 --> 46:57.190
Puerto Ayora.

46:58.450 --> 47:03.730
There they found a boat, the sea lion, to take

47:03.730 --> 47:07.570
them to Isabella, about 90 kilometers away.

47:08.650 --> 47:14.730
At first, the boatman Gonzalo did not want to take

47:14.730 --> 47:14.970
them.

47:16.050 --> 47:20.390
My boat can take ten people, he said.

47:21.210 --> 47:26.790
It's a very good boat, but very expensive for only

47:26.790 --> 47:27.990
two people.

47:29.130 --> 47:30.470
Jude smiled at him.

47:31.470 --> 47:34.570
Not for two rich people.

47:35.190 --> 47:37.410
Rich, said Hawker.

47:38.230 --> 47:40.570
It's not our money, ouch!

47:42.330 --> 47:44.950
Jude hit him hard on the arm.

47:46.170 --> 47:49.510
Where on holiday, she told Gonzalo.

47:50.270 --> 47:54.670
We want to see the giant tortoises on Isabella.

47:55.610 --> 47:56.890
She looked at Hawker.

47:57.890 --> 47:58.790
Don't we?

47:59.630 --> 48:07.110
Uh, yes, that's right, said Hawker quickly, where very interested

48:07.110 --> 48:09.790
in the giant tortoises.

48:11.450 --> 48:15.650
On the way to Isabella Island, Jude read a book

48:15.650 --> 48:21.150
about the Galapagos, and Hawker watched the sea.

48:22.890 --> 48:29.190
Isabella is a very young island, Jude told him, and

48:29.190 --> 48:35.330
it has, listened to this, six volcanoes,

48:35.650 --> 48:39.470
one erupted only two years ago.

48:39.470 --> 48:44.050
Oh, that's great, said Hawker.

48:44.870 --> 48:49.770
Crazy emails, strange visitors in the middle of the Pacific,

48:50.590 --> 48:53.890
and now erupting volcanoes.

48:54.710 --> 48:56.090
Thank you, Arla.

48:57.650 --> 49:04.430
Not many people lived on Isabella, and Puerto Villamil was

49:04.430 --> 49:06.390
usually a sleepy place.

49:07.330 --> 49:12.090
But when the sea lion arrived, there were about fifty

49:12.090 --> 49:14.310
people down by the sea.

49:15.530 --> 49:21.910
There were two small boats, and on them Hawker and

49:21.910 --> 49:27.210
Jude could see chairs and tables, beds,

49:27.210 --> 49:32.010
boxes, and bags, and a bicycle.

49:33.990 --> 49:38.070
Gonzalo called out in Spanish to the people on the

49:38.070 --> 49:41.990
boats, then turned to Hawker and Jude.

49:43.170 --> 49:47.150
Lots of people are leaving Isabella, he said.

49:47.890 --> 49:49.250
They are afraid.

49:50.510 --> 49:51.850
Afraid of what?

49:51.850 --> 49:53.390
Asked Jude.

49:54.050 --> 49:56.190
Go and talk to them, Hawker.

49:56.950 --> 49:58.930
Your Spanish is better than mine.

50:00.470 --> 50:03.470
Hawker came back half an hour later.

50:04.790 --> 50:08.830
You're not going to believe this, he told Jude.

50:09.630 --> 50:14.590
The people here say there's a spaceship on Isabella.

50:14.590 --> 50:22.390
It came down ten days ago, right down inside Volcano

50:22.390 --> 50:26.070
Aceido, and it's still there.

50:27.110 --> 50:30.450
How do they know that, said Jude?

50:31.610 --> 50:36.810
There's an Australian, Dr. Jim Miller, up on Aceido.

50:37.770 --> 50:41.910
He works here, studying giant tortoises.

50:41.910 --> 50:47.830
He saw the spaceship, and now he's waiting for the

50:47.830 --> 50:49.990
visitors to come out.

50:51.410 --> 50:59.790
So, the visitors in those emails are extraterrestrials, E.T.'s

50:59.790 --> 51:03.590
little green men from another planet.

51:03.590 --> 51:06.950
Oh, dear, said Jude.

51:07.810 --> 51:10.530
Can we go home now, Hawker?

51:11.310 --> 51:12.430
Hawker laughed.

51:13.650 --> 51:15.930
No, we can't.

51:16.330 --> 51:20.110
We climb Volcano Aceido, he said.

51:20.890 --> 51:22.450
Talk to Dr. Miller.

51:23.470 --> 51:25.870
Say hello to the E.T.'s.

51:26.450 --> 51:29.590
Oh, dear, Jude said again.

51:29.590 --> 51:31.950
I was afraid of that.

51:33.910 --> 51:38.330
Gonzalo took them in the sea lion up to Shipton

51:38.330 --> 51:38.630
Cove.

51:39.950 --> 51:45.590
There, very early the next morning, Hawker and Jude began

51:45.590 --> 51:48.130
their climb up the volcano.

51:49.230 --> 51:54.470
There is a path, Gonzalo told them, but it is

51:54.470 --> 51:58.370
five hours to the top, and hard climbing,

51:59.010 --> 52:01.730
and very, very hot.

52:02.630 --> 52:09.730
You must carry water, two liters for one person, for

52:09.730 --> 52:10.750
one day.

52:11.750 --> 52:17.250
You must sleep at the top and come down tomorrow,

52:18.210 --> 52:22.190
but not when the sun is high in the sky.

52:23.290 --> 52:26.510
And be careful, please.

52:28.230 --> 52:31.150
Careful of the spaceship visitors, you mean?

52:31.910 --> 52:32.470
Said Jude.

52:33.470 --> 52:41.870
I don't know about spaceships, smiled Gonzalo, but Volcano Aceido

52:41.870 --> 52:44.570
is always a little excited.

52:46.010 --> 52:49.310
She is always doing something new.

52:51.210 --> 52:54.050
It was a very hard climb.

52:55.050 --> 52:59.130
After two hours, they stopped under some trees.

53:00.130 --> 53:04.670
They drank some water and looked out over the blue

53:04.670 --> 53:05.210
sea.

53:06.510 --> 53:11.570
The black volcanic rocks under their feet were hot from

53:11.570 --> 53:12.030
the sun.

53:13.030 --> 53:17.890
It's so beautiful here, said Jude.

53:18.650 --> 53:23.130
Hmm, yes and no, said Hawker.

53:23.730 --> 53:32.550
Then, hey, Jude, look that animal over there by that

53:32.550 --> 53:32.850
rock.

53:33.570 --> 53:35.570
What is it?

53:36.770 --> 53:39.810
Oh, wow, whispered Jude.

53:40.810 --> 53:41.950
It's an iguana.

53:43.430 --> 53:45.150
A Galapagos iguana.

53:46.210 --> 53:48.250
Isn't he wonderful?

53:50.310 --> 53:54.770
The iguana stared at them with its hot orange eyes

53:54.770 --> 53:56.930
and did not move.

53:57.990 --> 54:03.270
Its body was about a meter long and an orange

54:03.270 --> 54:04.670
yellowy color.

54:05.670 --> 54:11.830
It looks about a thousand years old, said Hawker, a

54:11.830 --> 54:13.590
very strange animal.

54:14.790 --> 54:20.310
Everything about this island is strange, said Jude.

54:21.390 --> 54:26.930
They climbed and climbed, and the sun got hotter and

54:26.930 --> 54:27.210
hotter.

54:28.970 --> 54:34.730
After three more hours, they came to the top and

54:34.730 --> 54:37.970
looked down into the great crater of

54:37.970 --> 54:44.990
Alcedo, two hundred meters deep and seven kilometers across.

54:46.070 --> 54:50.510
To the north and the south, they could see more

54:50.510 --> 54:54.790
volcanoes and across the sea to the west,

54:54.790 --> 54:58.110
the island of Fernandina.

54:59.350 --> 55:04.050
But they could not see Dr. Miller or his camp.

55:05.210 --> 55:08.950
We need to go round the crater to the south,

55:09.450 --> 55:10.190
said Hawker.

55:10.970 --> 55:14.910
It's another two hours walk, the villagers said.

55:16.050 --> 55:21.270
It was hard walking over the black lava rock, and

55:21.270 --> 55:23.430
once Hawker nearly fell,

55:23.430 --> 55:25.890
Jude caught his arm.

55:27.030 --> 55:29.710
Don't break a leg here, she said.

55:30.290 --> 55:32.790
I don't want to carry you back down to the

55:32.790 --> 55:33.050
boat.

55:34.070 --> 55:36.710
Why not, said Hawker.

55:37.450 --> 55:39.290
I carried you home once.

55:40.390 --> 55:45.290
We weren't on top of a volcano then, said Jude.

55:46.290 --> 55:51.930
At last, they saw Dr. Miller's camp, and ten minutes

55:51.930 --> 55:53.770
later, they arrived.

55:54.910 --> 56:00.750
Dr. Miller was short, very brown, and angry.

56:01.530 --> 56:04.490
Go away, he shouted.

56:05.490 --> 56:08.330
You're Americans, aren't you?

56:09.450 --> 56:12.730
No, we aren't, said Hawker.

56:13.470 --> 56:14.290
We're European.

56:15.410 --> 56:17.250
How do you do, Dr. Miller?

56:18.010 --> 56:20.330
What are you doing here?

56:21.330 --> 56:22.130
He said angrily.

56:23.450 --> 56:29.910
We'd like to talk to you, said Jude quietly, about

56:29.910 --> 56:32.370
the spaceship down in the crater.

56:33.250 --> 56:35.370
Why are you so angry?

56:36.370 --> 56:42.030
Because nobody listens to me, said Dr. Miller.

56:42.730 --> 56:45.070
Nobody believes me.

56:46.210 --> 56:50.010
The Americans say, oh, crazy man.

56:51.130 --> 56:55.210
The Australian government says, get some sleep.

56:56.270 --> 56:57.770
What can I do?

56:58.990 --> 57:05.250
Something very important is happening on this planet, and nobody

57:05.250 --> 57:06.630
is listening.

57:07.750 --> 57:13.790
Well, we're here now, and we're listening, Jude said.

57:15.110 --> 57:16.870
Dr. Miller looked at them.

57:17.870 --> 57:19.810
Who do you work for?

57:20.810 --> 57:22.910
Europe, said Hawker.

57:23.650 --> 57:26.910
Europe is very interested in this spaceship.

57:27.850 --> 57:30.430
Please, tell us about it.

57:31.570 --> 57:37.310
Ah, the emails did get through then, said Dr. Miller.

57:38.390 --> 57:43.290
Who did the emails come from, asked Hawker?

57:45.070 --> 57:50.890
Ecuadorian friends, said Dr. Miller, over on Santa Cruz.

57:52.030 --> 57:55.050
Look, I've got some beer here.

57:55.830 --> 57:56.850
You want one?

57:58.110 --> 58:02.090
They sat on the black lava rocks under the hot

58:02.090 --> 58:05.250
sun, and drank hot beer.

58:06.690 --> 58:12.750
Below them, clouds of smoke and steam moved this way

58:12.750 --> 58:15.410
and that way across the crater,

58:16.350 --> 58:22.790
and was there under those clouds, a spaceship from another

58:22.790 --> 58:23.370
planet?

58:24.970 --> 58:30.870
Sometimes I think I can see it down there, said

58:30.870 --> 58:34.690
Jim Miller, but mostly I can't.

58:35.520 --> 58:40.830
It's a great white thing, and long legs came out

58:40.830 --> 58:42.410
of it when it came down.

58:43.390 --> 58:46.490
But why here, Jim, said Jude?

58:47.390 --> 58:49.310
Why, into a volcano?

58:50.370 --> 58:56.690
Who knows, said Jim, perhaps they like hot places.

58:57.450 --> 59:01.010
Perhaps they need something from the hot lava.

59:02.670 --> 59:05.930
And why are you angry with the Americans, Jim?

59:06.650 --> 59:11.270
Hawker asked, I know their beer is no good, but

59:11.270 --> 59:15.470
they watch this spaceship on their satellite.

59:16.310 --> 59:17.690
I know they did.

59:18.330 --> 59:22.810
They know it's here, but they don't want the world

59:22.810 --> 59:23.590
to know.

59:24.470 --> 59:28.630
They don't want people like you and me to meet

59:28.630 --> 59:30.930
any extraterrestrial visitors.

59:31.930 --> 59:36.190
Oh no, they want it all to be a big

59:36.190 --> 59:36.790
secret.

59:37.710 --> 59:40.450
Then they can be top dog.

59:41.810 --> 59:47.470
Just then, there was a sudden noise, a boom, deep

59:47.470 --> 59:48.410
below the ground.

59:49.410 --> 59:49.950
What?

59:50.390 --> 59:52.230
What was that, Jim?

59:52.890 --> 59:53.630
Asked Jude.

59:54.490 --> 59:59.690
Oh, how sado does that all the time, said Jim.

01:00:00.370 --> 01:00:06.990
Then hot water comes up, and steam, dust, sometimes a

01:00:06.990 --> 01:00:09.130
little lava, but not much.

01:00:09.930 --> 01:00:13.590
That's why there are always clouds in the crater.

01:00:14.510 --> 01:00:17.290
You can never see anything down there.

01:00:18.230 --> 01:00:21.490
Can we climb down into the crater?

01:00:22.450 --> 01:00:23.070
Asked Hawker.

01:00:23.730 --> 01:00:24.890
Are you crazy?

01:00:26.130 --> 01:00:29.270
It's dangerous down there, Jim said.

01:00:30.530 --> 01:00:36.090
All evening, Hawker and Jude stared down into the crater,

01:00:36.970 --> 01:00:39.630
but they could see nothing through

01:00:39.630 --> 01:00:41.810
the clouds of steam and dust.

01:00:43.370 --> 01:00:49.070
Just before the sun went down, Hawker saw something near

01:00:49.070 --> 01:00:52.210
the top of the crater and shouted to

01:00:52.210 --> 01:00:56.770
Jude, but it was only two of the giant tortoises.

01:00:57.670 --> 01:01:03.090
They came slowly past the camp and went away down

01:01:03.090 --> 01:01:04.590
the other side of the volcano.

01:01:06.530 --> 01:01:12.670
Later, four more came past, going the same way, moving

01:01:12.670 --> 01:01:15.850
slowly and quietly over the black

01:01:15.850 --> 01:01:16.110
rocks.

01:01:17.250 --> 01:01:21.330
Their very strange animals, said Jude.

01:01:23.470 --> 01:01:26.230
Hawker and Jude did not sleep much.

01:01:26.230 --> 01:01:31.830
The rocks were hard, and below them they heard again

01:01:31.830 --> 01:01:35.930
and again the deep boom of the volcano.

01:01:38.110 --> 01:01:41.790
Late in the night they turned their radio on.

01:01:42.930 --> 01:01:47.290
It was very noisy, but through the noise they could

01:01:47.290 --> 01:01:49.490
hear a voice from Santa Cruz.

01:01:50.790 --> 01:01:52.350
Hawker listened hard.

01:01:53.530 --> 01:01:58.550
They're talking about volcano Alcedo, he said.

01:01:59.670 --> 01:02:03.550
They think it's going to erupt in the next twenty

01:02:03.550 --> 01:02:04.410
-four hours.

01:02:05.310 --> 01:02:06.950
Jude sat up.

01:02:07.810 --> 01:02:08.590
Oh no!

01:02:09.710 --> 01:02:12.250
We're seven hours away from the boat.

01:02:13.290 --> 01:02:14.210
Let's get moving.

01:02:15.330 --> 01:02:16.410
Go and call Jim.

01:02:18.170 --> 01:02:22.570
But Jim Miller did not believe Santa Cruz radio.

01:02:23.470 --> 01:02:26.810
It's the Americans again, he said.

01:02:27.290 --> 01:02:29.870
They want us all to go away.

01:02:30.950 --> 01:02:33.970
Please come with us, Jim, said Jude.

01:02:34.570 --> 01:02:38.370
Please, you can come back in a day or two.

01:02:39.370 --> 01:02:45.370
You two go, said Jim, but I'm staying right here

01:02:45.370 --> 01:02:47.970
and watching that spaceship.

01:02:49.590 --> 01:02:51.970
It was a hard climb down.

01:02:52.850 --> 01:02:57.590
When they got to the sea they saw Gonzalo with

01:02:57.590 --> 01:02:58.250
the little boat.

01:02:59.390 --> 01:03:01.510
Hurry, he shouted.

01:03:02.410 --> 01:03:05.150
Did you hear on the radio?

01:03:06.410 --> 01:03:08.590
Alcedo's going to erupt.

01:03:10.050 --> 01:03:14.070
Quickly, they went out to the sea lion and climbed

01:03:14.070 --> 01:03:15.290
up onto the boat.

01:03:16.430 --> 01:03:18.950
Go, go, go!

01:03:19.970 --> 01:03:24.770
Gonzalo shouted to his men, and before long the sea

01:03:24.770 --> 01:03:27.590
lion was a kilometer out at sea.

01:03:29.070 --> 01:03:33.730
Two hours later, volcano Alcedo erupted.

01:03:35.190 --> 01:03:40.590
There was a sudden great bang, and then clouds of

01:03:40.590 --> 01:03:43.090
dust flew up into the sky.

01:03:44.610 --> 01:03:49.410
Red-hot lava came out of the volcano's sides and

01:03:49.410 --> 01:03:51.390
ran down to the sea.

01:03:52.390 --> 01:03:58.010
The noise did not stop, and with every bang rocks

01:03:58.010 --> 01:04:01.810
flew hundreds of meters up into the

01:04:01.810 --> 01:04:06.890
sky, then fell slowly back down to the ground.

01:04:08.110 --> 01:04:13.090
For hours the night sky was filled with great flowers

01:04:13.090 --> 01:04:15.870
of red and orange light.

01:04:15.870 --> 01:04:21.810
It was a beautiful and a terrifying thing to watch.

01:04:24.650 --> 01:04:27.050
What happened to Dr. Miller?

01:04:27.950 --> 01:04:28.390
I asked.

01:04:29.730 --> 01:04:34.210
Poor Jim went to the great spaceship in the sky,

01:04:34.870 --> 01:04:35.530
Jude said.

01:04:36.650 --> 01:04:42.070
Five hundred meters of red-hot lava fell on top

01:04:42.070 --> 01:04:42.430
of him.

01:04:43.430 --> 01:04:47.330
And was there a spaceship in the volcano?

01:04:47.950 --> 01:04:49.950
No, said Jude.

01:04:50.810 --> 01:04:53.370
Yes, said Hawker.

01:04:54.130 --> 01:04:57.470
He looked at Jude, and they laughed.

01:04:58.730 --> 01:05:00.630
Then Jude looked at me.

01:05:01.490 --> 01:05:04.130
What do you want to believe?

01:05:05.130 --> 01:05:05.430
She asked.

01:05:06.190 --> 01:05:10.490
They weren't very clever extraterrestrials, were they?

01:05:10.490 --> 01:05:15.930
Sitting there in their spaceship in an erupting volcano?

01:05:17.050 --> 01:05:18.370
Hawker smiled.

01:05:19.610 --> 01:05:25.650
Ah, but perhaps the spaceship left just before the volcano

01:05:25.650 --> 01:05:26.310
erupted.

01:05:27.630 --> 01:05:32.730
Gonzalo and I saw something in the clouds of dust.

01:05:33.730 --> 01:05:39.850
A white light moving very fast, faster than the dust.

01:05:39.850 --> 01:05:43.030
It went up very high.

01:05:43.870 --> 01:05:48.450
Well, I didn't see anything, said Jude.

01:05:49.290 --> 01:05:53.850
And that's because there wasn't anything in that volcano.

01:05:55.890 --> 01:05:58.670
Hawker looked up into the blue-greek sky.

01:05:59.990 --> 01:06:02.410
How do we know?

01:06:03.550 --> 01:06:04.190
He said slowly.

01:06:04.190 --> 01:06:11.610
One day, someone or something is going to visit us

01:06:11.610 --> 01:06:12.650
from out there.

01:06:13.830 --> 01:06:19.230
Perhaps that was the first visit all those years ago

01:06:19.230 --> 01:06:21.030
in the Galapagos.

01:06:22.330 --> 01:06:23.250
Who knows?

01:06:38.170 --> 01:06:39.570
Who knows?

